reviewText: This had all the right ingredients:  great cinematography, midling acting by good looking twenty-somethings, plausible and scary revenge twists, and a good kick of retribution/karma/justice.  Then -- if you get this far it's AFTER the car accident-and we've come full circle- the whole film all begins to unravel.  It's as if the editor just left the room and let the reel go.  The movie is no longer a movie - it's a three hour rehash left-turn to boringsville with self congratulatory morality and putrid saccharine lectures.  P. U.
summary: Great Premise Lost in Overbearing Length - Avoid It

reviewText: Need watch again before I return to library, but sometimes great acting, great plot, and interesting perspectives. I did not know Lucifer left heaven because of Pride, for example. I thought Lucifer was just plain a bad guy. If you can past all the lengthened sex scenes, and go to the acting... Glen Close the teacher, for example, and what the characters learn, and how they change, then this movie can be more than a titalating experience.
summary: Little long, but way cool ending!

reviewText: A modern  Dante with seven young people, each showcasing one of the seven deadly sins. The appeal is that of a serial or soap-opera, but the cast's working together creates a dynamic, realistic set of conflicts among teens who are close to graduation. Each makes his own mistakes, and each will account for his "sins." A very good flick, but beware--it is nearly three hours long.
summary: What a ramp in the circles of hell!
